{"cursor":"3622","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox publisher\n| image = parent = Bloomsbury Publishing status = founded = 1980 founder =\n| Werner Mark Linz successor = country = United Kingdom headquarters = London\n| distribution = keypeople = publications = Books topics = genre = imprints =\n| Burns & Oates, T&T Clark revenue = numemployees = nasdaq = url =\n}} 'Continuum International Publishing Group' is an academic publisher of books\nwith editorial offices in London and New York City. It had been owned by Nova\nCapital Management since 2005. In July 2011 it was taken over by Bloomsbury\nPublishing. As of September 2012, all new Continuum titles are\npublished under the Bloomsbury name (under the imprint Bloomsbury\nAcademic). ((cite web |url=http://www.bloomsbury.com/rebranding-continuum-berg-\nbcp/ |date=November 2012 | accessdate=November 23, 2012))\n\nContinuum International was created in 1999 with the merger of the Cassell\nacademic and religious lists and The Continuum Publishing Company, founded in\nNew York in 1980.\n\nThe academic publishing programme is focused on the humanities, especially the\nfields of philosophy, film and music, literature, education, linguistics,\ntheology, and biblical studies. Continuum publishes Paulo Freire's seminal\n[[Pedagogy of the Oppressed]].\n\nContinuum acquired Athlone Press, which was originally founded in 1948 as the\nUniversity of London publishing house and sold to the Bemrose Corporation in\n1979.\n\nIn 2003, Continuum acquired the London-based Hambledon & London {{cite web\n|url= http://www.continuumbooks.com/AboutUs/default.aspx?ImprintID=8&CountryID=1\n|title= about hambledon continuum |accessdate=2009-01-24 }}  ([[Sunday\nTimes]] Small Publisher of the Year 2001â02), {{cite web |url=\nhttp://www.hambledon.co.uk/system/index.html |title= Hambledon and London |accessdate=2009-01-\n24 }}  a publisher of trade history for the general reader.\n","linknr":146,"url":"Continuum_Inter